  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I re-apply for an H1B after cancelled without prejudice?",
  "response": "Reapplying for an H1B visa after it has been cancelled without prejudice involves several steps. \"Cancelled without prejudice\" generally means that the visa was not used and there was no negative implication attached to the cancellation. Here's how you can reapply:\n\n1. **Check Eligibility**:\n   - Ensure that you still meet all the requirements for an H1B visa. This includes having a valid job offer from a U.S. employer for a specialty occupation, and holding the necessary qualifications.\n\n2. **File a New Petition**:\n   - Your employer needs to file a new Form I-129, Petition for a Nonimmigrant Worker, with the United States Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS). This petition should include all necessary documentation to support the case, such as the Labor Condition Application (LCA) certified by the Department of Labor, evidence of your qualifications, and details about the offered position.\n\n3. **Pay the Required Fees**:\n   - Ensure all filing fees are paid when submitting the petition. This includes the standard H1B filing fee, the fraud prevention and detection fee, and possibly the premium processing fee if expedited processing is desired.\n\n4. **Wait for Approval**:\n   - Once your employer files the petition, you need to wait for approval from USCIS. This process might take several months unless premium processing is opted for.\n\n5. **Consular Processing (if applicable)**:\n   - If you are outside the U.S., after the petition is approved, you will need to apply for the visa at a U.S. consulate or embassy. This process includes completing the DS-160 form, paying the visa application fee, scheduling and attending a visa interview, and submitting necessary documentation.\n\n6. **Attend Visa Interview**:\n   - During your visa interview, be prepared to explain why your previous visa was cancelled, if asked. Provide necessary documents such as your new I-797 approval notice, current passport, employment verification letter, and any other required documents.\n\n7. **Receive Visa Approval**:\n   - If the consulate officer approves your application, you will receive your H1B visa stamped in your passport. \n\n8. **Travel to the U.S.**:\n   - Once you have your visa, you can travel to the U.S. and start your employment as per the details stated in your petition.\n\nImportant Considerations:\n- If your H1B visa was cancelled due to specific issues, ensure those issues are resolved before reapplying.\n- Be thorough and precise with all documentation to avoid delays or denials.\n\nIf needed, consider consulting an immigration attorney to guide you through the process and ensure that you meet all legal requirements and deadlines.",
